All students in grades 6-12 must go to the high school gym every morning in order to check their temperature to attend school. Students will enter through the Gym Lobby doors and follow social distancing guidelines to proceed through the temperature kiosks. A “grab and go” breakfast will be available in the gym lobby. Students who arrive after 8:15 a.m. will check in at the MS/HS for a temperature check and admit slip. Please direct any questions to Kristina Brown at 509-382-4775 or kristinab@daytonsd.org The following is the schedule for this week:

Tuesday, August 25th – 6th & 9th Grades
Wednesday, August 26th – 7th & 10th Grades
Thursday, August 27th – 8th, 11th & 12th Grades
Friday, August 28th – 6th – 12th Grades

Reminder that there is a 12:30 p.m. dismissal for 6-12th grades. Lunch will be available.

Registration days for 2020-21 school year will be as follows. Date and time for your student’s designated registration day is according to what your student’s last name begins with. If you have more than one student and their last name is not the same, please come on what day works best for you and register your students all at once.
A-D Aug 13th 10am-1pm in Multipurpose room
E-J Aug 14th 10am-1pm in Multipurpose room
K-S Aug 17th 10am-1pm in Multipurpose room
T-Z Aug 18th 10am-1pm in Multipurpose room
If you are unable to come during the designated time please stop by during our elementary and/or secondary office on Aug 19th or 21st from 8am-1pm. Please wear your mask and practice social distancing. The first day of school will be Aug 25th. So excited to see your faces! A plan for the school year is still being decided. The superintendent will be emailing parents over the weekend with a final plan.

post_text:
Students in grades K-12 are eligible for Pandemic EBT cards to help with buying groceries while school is closed for the summer. Families can apply by calling 877-501-2233 or online at www.WashingtonConnection.org. The application will be open by June 30th. (application is not currently open).

If your family receives Basic Food through DSHS and your children receive free or reduced-price school meals, you do not need to apply for P-EBT. You will automatically receive these one-time benefits on your EBT card. You will need to apply for P-EBT if your children are eligible for free or reduced-price school meals but do not receive Basic Food benefits.

Students in grades 6-12 who are not receiving Basic Food benefits but are receiving free or reduced priced meals are eligible for an EBT card. If you have had a change of income since school closed in March, families are eligible to fill out a free & reduced form and return it to the District office. Last day to turn in a new free & reduced form will be Thursday, June 25th.

Dayton FFA
April 15 at 3:30 PM ·

Plant spotlight #2: Petunias!

Always a popular plant! This year we have two types of petunias, sanguna series and headliner series. (See pictures for color options of both types!)

Sanguna series: Easy wave petunias that are very versatile for planting in containers, hanging baskets, or landscape beds! If you want flowers to trail over the edges of pots or baskets this should be your ideal choice!

Headliner series: quickly becoming a first choice for many due to its dramatic colors, medium-vigor and many blooms! More of a mounding growth habit that will still fill pots and baskets!

post_text: Fifth District member Cathy McMorris Rogers, of the federal House of Representatives, spoke with Dayton High School juniors and seniors on Monday, November 4th. McMorris Rogers spent some time talking about the federal government, Washington D.C., and the importance of our democracy. The remainder of the time was opened to student questions. Questions ranged from her goals in Congress and her position on several issues to the current impeachment proceedings. The four Dayton students currently in Washington DC on the CloseUp program sponsored by Kiwanis were able to participate via video chat during the meeting.

post_text: Mr. Pearson's wood shop classes are making/painting 125 new wooden crosses for the American Legion at the request of the County Commissioner Chuck Amerein. The crosses will be placed on Veterans' graves on Memorial Day in Dayton.
